Wistia Video Analytics Pipeline
================================

Overview
--------
This project is an end-to-end data engineering pipeline built to collect,
process, and analyze video engagement data from Wistia across Facebook and
YouTube channels. It was designed to simulate a real-world production data
pipeline with full responsibility for architecture, ingestion, transformation,
scheduling, testing, and documentation.

The pipeline runs automatically every day, pulls fresh data from the Wistia
Stats API, transforms it using PySpark, and stores the results in a structured
data model ready for analysis.


What This Pipeline Does
-----------------------
- Connects to the Wistia Stats API and pulls video engagement data
- Handles pagination to fetch all available records (60,000+ rows)
- Uses incremental ingestion so each daily run only pulls new data
- Transforms raw JSON into three clean structured tables using PySpark
- Runs automatically every day using a scheduled cron job
- Logs every run with timestamps, record counts, and error handling
- Tests are automatically run on every GitHub push using GitHub Actions


Tech Stack
----------
Language:        Python 3.13
Transformation:  PySpark 4.1.1
Version Control: Git and GitHub
CI/CD:           GitHub Actions
Scheduling:      Cron (macOS)
Testing:         pytest


Project Structure
-----------------
The project is organized into clear, separate layers following
standard data engineering best practices:

  src/ingestion/
    wistia_ingest.py       Fetches visitor-level events from the API
    media_metadata.py      Fetches media-level stats and metadata

  src/transformation/
    spark_transform.py     PySpark jobs to clean and structure raw data

  src/pipeline.py          Master script that runs the full pipeline in order

  tests/
    test_ingestion.py      Unit tests for ingestion logic

  .github/workflows/
    ci.yml                 GitHub Actions workflow for automated testing


Data Model
----------
The pipeline produces three structured tables:

  dim_media
    Stores information about each video
    Fields: media_id, channel (Facebook or YouTube)

  dim_visitor
    Stores information about each unique viewer
    Fields: visitor_id, ip_address, country

  fact_media_engagement
    Stores engagement events linking visitors to videos
    Fields: media_id, visitor_id, date, watched_percent


Pipeline Statistics
-------------------
  Total records processed:   59,861
  Unique visitors identified: 56,516
  Media IDs tracked:          2
  Daily schedule:             8:00 AM every day
  Incremental logic:          Yes, watermark-based


How To Set Up and Run
---------------------
Step 1 - Clone the repository

  git clone https://github.com/fosabdul/Wistia_Video_Analytics.git
  cd Wistia_Video_Analytics

Step 2 - Install dependencies

  pip3 install -r requirements.txt

Step 3 - Set up your environment variables
  Create a file called .env in the root folder and add:

  WISTIA_API_TOKEN=hidden

Step 4 - Run the full pipeline

  python3 src/pipeline.py

Step 5 - Run the tests

  python3 -m pytest tests/ -v


CI/CD Pipeline
--------------
Every time code is pushed to the main branch, GitHub Actions automatically:

  1. Sets up a clean Python environment
  2. Installs all dependencies
  3. Runs all unit tests
  4. Reports pass or fail status

This ensures the codebase is always in a working state.


Design Decisions
----------------
Incremental Ingestion
  Rather than pulling all 60,000 records on every run, the pipeline saves
  a watermark timestamp after each successful run. The next run only fetches
  records created after that timestamp, making daily runs fast and efficient.

Separation of Concerns
  Ingestion, transformation, and orchestration are kept in separate scripts.
  This makes each component easier to test, debug, and maintain independently.

Error Handling
  Every API call includes retry logic with exponential backoff. All errors
  are logged with timestamps so failures can be diagnosed quickly.

Raw Data Preservation
  Raw JSON responses are saved to disk before transformation. This means
  if the transformation logic needs to change, data can be reprocessed
  without hitting the API again.


